EXPERIMENT 2
Context Window Compression: Preserving What Matters
Memory Compression Layer · mem0 · LangGraph · Working Memory Management

Hypothesis
Progressive summarization with entity-aware compression retains >90% of decision-relevant information while reducing token consumption by 60–80% compared to naive truncation. The Information Retention Quotient (IRQ) metric quantifies this tradeoff precisely.

Why This Matters for Enterprise
Every AI agent with memory faces an economics problem: context windows are finite and expensive. The naive solution — truncating old turns — destroys exactly the information that made memory valuable in the first place. This experiment tests four compression strategies and introduces IRQ as the metric that enterprise teams need but do not yet have: a single number measuring how much decision-relevant information survives compression.

Data Specification
Conversation Dataset — 50 Long-Horizon Sessions per Domain
•	3 domains × 50 sessions × avg 15 turns = 2,250 total conversation turns
•	Domains: data analysis dialogues, IT support escalations, HR onboarding conversations
•	Each session has annotated 'decision-critical entities' — facts that must survive compression to answer a late-turn question correctly
•	Downstream evaluation task per session: 10 factual questions about early turns, answerable only if compression preserved key entities

Compression Strategy Configurations
Strategy	Method	Expected IRQ
FIFO Truncation	Drop oldest turns when limit reached	Low — drops critical early context
Static Summarization	Summarize all old turns into one block	Medium — loses entity specificity
Entity-Aware Progressive	Extract + preserve named entities, compress narrative	High — your proposed winner
Importance-Scored Retention	Score each turn by relevance to current query, retain top K	High — dynamic but expensive

Tools Active in This Experiment
Tool	Role	Notes
LangGraph	Stateful agent + compression hooks	Custom node for each compression strategy
mem0	Memory add/update lifecycle	Handles entity extraction + versioned memory updates
spaCy / NER	Named entity extraction	Identifies entities to preserve across compression
GPT-4o-mini	Compression LLM + agent LLM	Generates summaries + answers downstream questions
tiktoken	Token counting	Measure actual token reduction per strategy
W&B Weave	Experiment tracking	Log IRQ, token counts, accuracy per strategy per session

Metrics & Named Contribution
Metric	Formula	Why It Matters
Information Retention Quotient (IRQ) ★	(Downstream Task Accuracy with Compressed Memory) / (Accuracy with Full Memory) × 100	YOUR named metric — single number for compression quality
Token Reduction Ratio	(Original tokens − Compressed tokens) / Original tokens × 100	Cost savings signal
Entity Preservation Rate	% annotated critical entities surviving compression	Mechanism behind IRQ — what is actually being lost?
IRQ vs Token Reduction Curve	Plot IRQ at 20%, 40%, 60%, 80% token reduction	The Pareto frontier — where compression stops being worth it
Coherence Score	LLM judge: does compressed context read coherently?	Guards against high IRQ with incoherent summaries

Experimental Conditions
•	4 compression strategies (FIFO / Static / Entity-Aware / Importance-Scored) × 3 domains × 50 sessions = 600 experiment runs
•	Held constant: LLM model, embedding model, downstream evaluation questions, token budget ceiling (2,000 tokens for compressed history)
•	Variable: compression algorithm only

