EXPERIMENT 4
Memory Staleness & TTL: When Memory Becomes a Liability
Memory Freshness Layer · Redis TTL · Confidence Decay · mem0

Hypothesis
Unmanaged memory staleness degrades agent decision quality by >40% after 30 days in dynamic enterprise domains. TTL-aware memory with confidence decay scoring reduces this degradation to <8%.

Why This Matters for Enterprise
Memory without expiry is a liability. Enterprise environments change constantly — org charts update, policies revise, systems change, products get deprecated. An agent that confidently cites 6-month-old facts can cause more damage than a stateless agent that admits it does not know. This experiment measures memory degradation over time and tests three staleness management strategies.

Data Specification
Temporal Enterprise Knowledge Base
•	Simulated enterprise environment with controlled change events over a 60-day window
•	3 domains with different change velocities: IT Systems (high — weekly changes), HR Policies (medium — monthly), Legal Compliance (low — quarterly)
•	100 'knowledge items' per domain seeded at T=0 with ground truth values
•	Change schedule: 30% of items modified at T+7, T+14, T+30, T+60 — simulating realistic enterprise knowledge drift

Evaluation Timeline
•	Agent memory seeded at T=0
•	Decision quality measured at T=0, T+7, T+14, T+30, T+60 days
•	50 test queries per domain per time point — total 1,500 evaluations across timeline

Tools Active in This Experiment
Tool	Role	Staleness Configuration
Redis (Docker)	TTL-aware memory store	Key-level TTL: IT=7d, HR=30d, Legal=90d
mem0	Memory update + versioning	Tracks memory age, update history, confidence score
Custom decay scorer	Confidence decay function	MFS = base_confidence × e^(−λ × days) where λ = domain decay rate
ChromaDB	Episodic memory with metadata	Stores creation_time, last_verified, confidence per item
LangGraph	Agent loop with freshness checks	Pre-retrieval filter: exclude items below MFS threshold

Metrics & Named Contribution
Metric	Formula / Method	What It Reveals
Memory Freshness Score (MFS) ★	MFS = confidence × e^(−λ × days_since_update)	YOUR named metric — per-item temporal confidence weight
Decision Accuracy vs Time	% correct decisions at each time point	Primary staleness degradation curve
False Confidence Rate	Agent states stale fact confidently / total stale facts surfaced	Most dangerous metric — silent wrong answers
Refresh Cost	API calls + compute per selective refresh cycle	Cost of keeping memory fresh — is it worth it?
Domain Decay Lambda (λ)	Fit exponential decay curve per domain	Calibrates domain-specific TTL recommendations

Experimental Conditions
#	Strategy	Mechanism	Expected Outcome
A	No staleness management	Memory never expires or refreshes	Worst — >40% accuracy drop by day 30
B	Fixed TTL expiry	Hard expiry based on domain (IT=7d, HR=30d)	Better — but wastes still-valid memory
C	Confidence decay + selective refresh	MFS-scored, refresh only when MFS < threshold	Best — efficient + accurate

