EXPERIMENT 5
Multi-Agent Shared Memory: Coordination Without Contamination
Collective Memory Layer · CrewAI · LangGraph · Neo4j · Redis

Hypothesis
A role-scoped shared memory architecture reduces inter-agent redundancy by >60% and improves multi-agent task completion rate by >35%, while maintaining memory isolation that prevents cross-role contamination — including adversarial injection.

Why This Matters for Enterprise
The final and hardest problem in the series: when multiple AI agents share memory, they can amplify each other's intelligence — or each other's errors. Role-scoped memory with write-access controls is the architectural pattern that makes shared memory safe in production. This experiment is the culmination of everything proven in E0–E4: memory matters, the right backend matters, retrieval quality matters, freshness matters — and now, isolation matters.

Data Specification
Multi-Agent Enterprise Workflow Dataset
•	5-agent enterprise system: Planner, Researcher, Writer, Reviewer, Coordinator
•	50 complete workflow tasks: each task requires all 5 agents to collaborate
•	Task domains: quarterly report generation (finance), technical RFP responses (sales/engineering), compliance audit preparation (legal/ops)

Contamination Test Injection Set
•	20 adversarial injection scenarios — deliberate false facts injected into shared memory by one agent
•	Measure how far injected misinformation propagates across other agents
•	Test whether role-scoped isolation blocks propagation

Tools Active in This Experiment
Tool	Role	Multi-Agent Configuration
LangGraph Multi-Agent	Agent graph orchestration	5-node agent graph with shared state store
CrewAI	Agent role definition	Role = Agent type with write-scope restriction
Neo4j AuraDB	Collective memory graph	Shared knowledge with role-tagged nodes + edges
Redis	Role-scoped working memory	Per-role namespaced keys — cross-role reads allowed, writes restricted
ChromaDB	Shared episodic memory	Collection-level access controls per agent role
Langfuse	Multi-agent tracing	Full inter-agent communication trace — invaluable for Series #3

Metrics & Named Contribution
Metric	Measurement	What It Proves
Task Completion Quality	Human eval 1–5 + LLM judge	Does shared memory improve output quality?
Inter-Agent Redundancy Rate	% redundant API calls eliminated	Does shared memory reduce wasted work?
Retrieval Contamination Rate (RCR) ★	% injected false facts surfaced by other agents	YOUR named metric — measures isolation effectiveness
Memory Write Conflict Rate	Concurrent write collisions / total writes	Measures coordination overhead of shared memory
Coordination Overhead	Extra LLM calls needed for clarification	Does shared memory reduce or increase communication?

Experimental Conditions
#	Architecture	Memory Access Model	Expected Outcome
A	Fully Isolated	No shared memory — agents cannot read each other's memory	High redundancy, low contamination risk
B	Fully Shared Flat	All agents read/write to same pool	Lower redundancy, high contamination risk
C	Role-Scoped Shared	Read-all, write-own-scope only	Hypothesis winner: efficient + safe
D	Hierarchical + Access Controls	Role-scoped + approval gate for cross-scope writes	Most controlled — highest overhead

